In the firſt place, There were great Contentions between the Biſhops, which is expreſly affirmed by Euſebius, cap. xiii. lib. 3. of the Life of Conſtantine; though Conſtantine, in a grave Speech, exhorted them all to Peace and Unanimity: Theſe are his words; 
                     〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                  , &c. Some began to accuſe their Neighbours, while others defended themſelves, and returned the Accuſation upon their Opponents. Neither could their Wranglings be compoſed any otherwiſe, than by throwing their Petitions into the fire.
